This paper discusses the design of Oblivious RAM (ORAM) for modern processors, specifically Intel SGX. This topic falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR) as it deals with protecting confidential data from being leaked. The paper also discusses the optimization of ORAM for online bandwidth cost and small blocks, which falls under the category of distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC) and data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The implementation of the Pyramid ORAM is also discussed, which falls under the category of software engineering (cs.SE). Finally, the paper discusses the comparison of Pyramid ORAM with Circuit ORAM, which falls under the category of computer architecture (cs.AR).
